Distribution, ecology and current population status.
Atelopus podocarpus
is only known from paramo and subparamo habitats in the southern Cordillera Oriental of Ecuador (Provincias Loja and Zamora Chinchipe) to Departamento Piura in Cordillera de Huancabamba in northern Peru (
Fig. 5
). In Ecuador , it occurs in the following Natural Formations (classification proposed by
Valencia et al. 1999
): Herbazal Lacustre Montano, Páramo Arbustivo, Bosque Siempre Verde Montano Alto, and Bosque de Neblina Montano. These habitats lie between 2700–3400 m (
Fig. 5
). Annual mean rainfall is 1000–2000 mm and annual mean temperature is 7–18 ºC (
Cañadas-Cruz, 1983
). The area of its extent of occurrence is of about 2475 km 2 . Habitat and other features of the Podocarpus National Park were described by
Rivera-Rosi ( 2007 )
.
